class Solution {
public:
    bool isSymmetric(TreeNode* root) {
        return root==NULL || isMirror(root->left, root->right);
    }
    bool isMirror(TreeNode* lefty, TreeNode* righty){
        if(lefty==NULL || righty==NULL) return lefty==righty;
        if(lefty->val!=righty->val) return false;
        return isMirror(lefty->left, righty->right) && isMirror(lefty->right, righty->left);
    }
};

"Idea:
This solution checks whether a binary tree is symmetric by comparing the left and right subtrees as mirror images.
The main function calls isMirror() for the left and right child of the root.

In isMirror(), if either node becomes NULL, it returns whether both are equal (NULL).
Then it checks if the values of both nodes are the same. If not, the tree is not symmetric.
After that, recursion is used to compare:

left child of the left subtree with right child of the right subtree
right child of the left subtree with left child of the right subtree

If both recursive checks return true, the tree is symmetric.
"

#Time complexity:- O(n)                Space Complexity:- O(h) where h = height of the tree
